    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#boardman-hayes1973"/>, n. <citedRange>F171</citedRange> (dr.)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>003810</citedRange></bibl>.</p>          
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                        <ab><lb n="1" rend="right-to-left"/><space extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <orig>ταμ</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	              </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمه بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>It is the editor's view that the letters should be read from right to left. No letter-form is compulsory. However
                    a vacat seems to exist at right of T, a letter with which no Greek word could end. We thus follow his reading.</p>
                <p>Due to the date given by Boardman for the ware, it seems compulsory to read the third letter as a mu, because san, which would be another possible reading,
                is no longer in use at the time.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
